{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}
The '''Scottish Oceanographical Laboratory''' was founded in Nicolson Street, [[Edinburgh]] in 1906, by [[William Speirs Bruce]], who had travelled widely in the [[Antarctic]] and [[Arctic]] regions and had led the [[Scottish National Antarctic Expedition]] (SNAE) 1902&ndash;04. Bruce had originally studied medicine at the [[University of Edinburgh]], but had transferred his studies to the [[natural sciences]] and, through his varied experiences, had established a reputation as a polar scientist. He had also collected a large number of [[botany|botanical]], [[biology|biological]], [[zoology|zoological]] and [[geology|geological]] specimens, together with vast amounts of [[meteorology|meteorological]] and [[magnetism|magnetic]] data.  The laboratory, established in [[Edinburgh]] at premises in Nicolson Street, provided a place to examine, store or display these materials, an office from which Bruce could work on the SNAE scientific reports, and a base from which further expeditions could be planned.<ref name = Speak>Speak, pp. 97&ndash;101</ref>

It was Bruce's ambition that the laboratory should develop into a Scottish National Oceanographical Institute. A meeting to discuss this possibility was held in May 1914, and the proposal gained significant support from leading Scottish scientists. An organising committee was established, but the matter was shelved on the outbreak of war in August 1914 and was not revived.<ref name = Speak/> In 1919 lack of funding, combined with his failing health, forced Bruce to close the laboratory, donating the various specimens, books and other materials to the University of Edinburgh, the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] and the [[National Museums of Scotland|Royal Scottish Museum]].<ref name = Speak/> His illness ended with his death in 1921.

